Volume = {{71}},
Pages = {{49-58}},
Month = {{NOV}},
Abstract = {{Geoinformation and Communication Technology (GeoICT) is being
   increasingly adopted to foster urban sustainability and smart cities.
   Despite the burgeoning utilization of GeoICT, the development of
   frameworks of components and guidelines is still at the infancy. This is
   due to the fact that GeoICT implementations are guided by contextual
   factors and there is no one size fits all approach. This paper focuses
   on the topic of leveraging GeoICT for smart sustainable cities by
   examining the Saudi Arabian experience using information from the
   literature, government websites, official documents, newspaper articles
   and personal interviews. This study reviews the definitions, typologies,
   and frameworks of implementing GeoICT and smart cities. It highlights
   case studies of sniart city development in Saudi Arabia. A comparison of
   the Saudi case studies with frameworks and practices found in the
   literature is presented. This paper concludes with policy implications
   for Saudi Arabia and lessons for GeoICT and smart city development. It
   is concluded that local context has an influence on the implementation
   of smart cities, ICT infrastructure is necessary but not sufficient for
   developing smart cities and blending top-down with bottom-up approaches
   is essential.}},
