   field of noise management is to involve citizens and facilitate their
   participation in urban environmental decisions. The SENSEable Pisa
   project, based on the concept of RealTime City and Smart City, presents
   an acoustic urban monitoring system based on a low-cost data acquisition
   method for a pervasive outdoor noise measurement. The system is based on
   the use of noise sensors located on private houses in the center of
   Pisa, which provide a good model for the current acoustic climate of
   Mediterranean city centers. In this study, SENSEable acquisitions show a
   strong anthropogenic component not revealed by public strategic maps.
   The anthropogenic component, commonly known as movida, becomes
   increasingly critical in Mediterranean cities, therefore, it is
   necessary to explore methods highlighting this new source and to adopt
