Month = {{JUL}},
Abstract = {{This paper focuses on the role of networked microgrids as distributed
   systems for enhancing the power system resilience against extreme
   events. Resilience is an intrinsically complex property which requires
   deep understanding of microgrid operation in order to respond
   effectively in emergency conditions. The paper first introduces the
   definition and offers a generic framework for analyzing the power system
   resilience. The notion that large power systems can achieve a higher
   level of resilience through the deployment of networked microgrids is
   discussed in detail. In particular, the management of networked
   microgrids for riding through extreme events is analyzed. In addition,
   the merits of advanced information and communication technologies (ICTs)
   in microgrid-based distributed systems that can support the power system
   resilience are presented. The paper also points out the challenges for
   expanding the role of distributed systems and concludes that networked
   microgrids in particular provide a universal solution for improving the
   resilience against extreme events in Smart Cities.}},
