Year = {{2017}},
Volume = {{90}},
Pages = {{16-30}},
Month = {{JUN}},
Abstract = {{Cities need to adapt to ageing societies because the average age of
   habitants is increasing rapidly alongside the global trend of
   urbanisation. Apparent effects on both society and individual
   livelihoods will continue to increase in the coming decades. Great hopes
   are projected on technology to support solutions for the ageing society
   and urban planning. Smart city strategies and the field of ambient
   assisted living are two concepts sharing the assumption that technology
   will make our lives more independent, more efficient and safer with a
   higher quality of life. This paper presents a case study of a
   participatory foresight project that investigates how transdisciplinary
   agenda setting through the means of including citizens, experts and
   stakeholders can provide orientation for long-term planning on the
   future of ageing in the city. Results enforce the argument that urban
   governance needs to address additional tasks whilst adapting to
   challenges arising from ageing societies and urbanisation. Alongside
   mere technological innovation, human factors gain importance.
   Future-oriented urban development strategies need to incorporate this
   fact and should not predominantly be drafted on the paradigm of
   technological progress.}},
